<span id="xiii.ii.i.i-p81"></span> This Alexander had been one of the
Nicene Fathers, in 325, and had the office of publishing their decrees
in Macedonia, Greece, &c. He was at the Council of Jerusalem ten years
after, at which the Church of the Holy Sepulchre was consecrated, and
afterwards Arius admitted to communion. His influence with the Court
party seems to have been great, judging from Count Dionysius’s tone in
speaking of him. Infr. §§66, 80, 81.

